{
  "texts": [
    "Taking into account that the associated sequence of n-tuples has length Tn + 1, we thus consider the points ðt i À n + 1, D n ðtÞÞ È É i = 1,..., k in logarithmic scale, i.e., ðx i, y i Þ = ðlog 10 ðt i À n + 1Þ, log 10 ðD n ðtÞÞÞ, ð2Þ",
    "with i = 1, …, k. In order to neglect the initial transient regime, but still have enough points for a sufficiently significant fit, we select only the last 100 of such points.",
    "We hence look for the best fit of fðx i, y i Þg i = kÀ100 + 1,..., k by optimizing the linear function y = a + b x, with a ≥ 0, using the tool curve_fit of Python package Scipy 91.",
    "The constraint a≥0 is necessary to avoid that the fitted Heaps' exponent is greater than 1, which could happen when the initial transient regime differs significantly from the asymptotic one and could hence produce wrong fits.",
    "Finally, if a and b are the best parameters, then the powerlaw fit of the Heaps' law is D n ðtÞ % 10 a t b, that is, the n th -order Heaps' exponent is approximated by the slope b of the fit."
  ]
}